 QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Several reasons for this.  Probably one of the biggest is that ND3's effect you can see.  You can clearly see your hp go up by ~400+, whereas the effects of CS3/CA3 aren't quite as clear as to *exactly* how, when, and under what circumstances they work.<br>
<br>
Also, keep in mind that CS3 and CA3 improve only your melee damage intake, ND3 benefits you on AE's, procs, *anything* that is coming your way.  Remember too, ND3 effects also your stamina, buffed or unbuffed.  Right now you may have 3300 hp but when you have 4500 unbuffed hp your looking at a much larger benefit.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>ONE single missed swing will be beneficial over that marginal hp gain many many times over.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The only parsed data we have available to us (Sscaley's logs) lends us to believe that ID/LR give you 1% increase in their respective mitigation/avoidance bonuses.  Using that as a guide, you get 1% average less damage for 3aa.  Now look at PD3, you get <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>1.5%</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> hp for 3aa spent.  PE evens out to 2.5aa for 1%, both better deals than ID/LR.  Add that to the fact that hp gains benefit you on both spell/melee damage, and thats why I prioritized pd3/pe over id/lr.<br>
<br>
Is this 1%-1.5% stuff a big deal?  Naah, all these skills are good enough to be done in whatever order you feel benefits you the best, I'm just explaining why the hp before ID/LR can be a good choice. <p>Veteran <a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=34639>Damacis Bigadanu</a>
